<section epub:type="chapter" role="doc-chapter" data-index="3">
<header data-index="4">
<h1 data-index="5"><a id="start" data-index="6"></a><span epub:type="pagebreak" role="doc-pagebreak" title="10-1" id="Page_10-1" data-index="7"></span> <span class="chapterNumber" data-index="8">CHAPTER 10</span> <br data-index="9"><span class="chapterTitle" data-index="10">Acquisition and Disposition of Property, Plant, and Equipment</span></h1>
</header>
<section data-index="11">
<figure data-index="12">
<img class="center" src="https://ereader-books-prod.chegg.com/682/9781119503682/39c53495-be04-40a4-af01-80a39a7df223/OPS/images/Co_fmt.jpg" alt="" data-index="13" data-size="%7B%22width%22%3A1313%2C%22height%22%3A113%7D">
<p class="right" data-index="14">© andersphoto/Shutterstock&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
</figure>
<aside data-index="15">
<div class="top hr" data-index="16"><hr data-index="17"></div>
<section class="feature1" style=" background-color: E1F4FD;" data-index="18">
<h3 id="h2_001" class="red" data-index="19">LEARNING OBJECTIVES</h3>
<p data-index="20">After studying this chapter, you should be able to:</p>
<p class="latin2" data-index="21"><span class="label" data-index="22"><a href="#h3_0003" data-index="23" data-section-index="20" data-section-idref="h3_0003" data-target-data-index="216"><b class="red" data-index="24">1.</b></a>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span> Identify property, plant, and equipment and its related costs.</p>
<p class="latin2" data-index="25"><span class="label" data-index="26"><a href="#h3_00010" data-index="27" data-section-index="20" data-section-idref="h3_00010" data-target-data-index="396"><b class="red" data-index="28">2.</b></a>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span> Discuss the accounting problems associated with interest capitalization.</p>
<p class="latin2" data-index="29"><span class="label" data-index="30"><a href="#h3_00022" data-index="31" data-section-index="20" data-section-idref="h3_00022" data-target-data-index="1296"><b class="red" data-index="32">3.</b></a>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span> Explain the accounting issues related to acquiring and valuing plant assets.</p>
<p class="latin2" data-index="33"><span class="label" data-index="34"><a href="#h3_00032" data-index="35" data-section-index="20" data-section-idref="h3_00032" data-target-data-index="2304"><b class="red" data-index="36">4.</b></a>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span> Describe the accounting treatment for costs subsequent to acquisition.</p>
<p class="latin2" data-index="37"><span class="label" data-index="38"><a href="#h3_00039" data-index="39" data-section-index="20" data-section-idref="h3_00039" data-target-data-index="2580"><b class="red" data-index="40">5.</b></a>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span> Describe the accounting treatment for the disposal of property, plant, and equipment.</p>
<div class="bottom hr" data-index="41"><hr data-index="42"></div>
</section>
</aside>
<br data-index="43">
<aside id="c10-feafxd-000PP" data-index="44">
<div class="top hr" data-index="45"><hr data-index="46"></div>
<section class="feature3" data-index="47">
<h3 id="h3_0001" data-index="48"><span class="codeColorGreen2" data-index="49">PREVIEW OF CHAPTER 10</span></h3>
<p data-index="50">As we indicate in the following opening story, a company like <span class="red" data-index="51"><b data-index="52">Jet Blue Airways</b></span> has a substantial investment in property, plant, and equipment. Conversely, other companies, such as <span class="red" data-index="53"><b data-index="54">Microsoft</b></span>, have a relatively minor investment in these types of assets. In this chapter, we discuss the proper accounting for the acquisition, use, and disposition of property, plant, and equipment. The content and organization of the chapter are as follows.</p>
<p data-index="55"><span style=" background-color: #127987; color: #FFFFFF;" data-index="56">This chapter also includes numerous conceptual and global discussions that are integral to the topics presented here. <b data-index="57"><i data-index="58">IFRS Insights</i></b> related to PPE are presented in Chapter 11.</span></p>
<figure data-index="59">
<img class="center" src="https://ereader-books-prod.chegg.com/682/9781119503682/39c53495-be04-40a4-af01-80a39a7df223/OPS/images/c10/t0010.jpg" alt="An illustration titled Preview of Chapter 10, reads, As we indicate in the opening story, a company like Jet Blue Airways has a substantial investment in property, plant, and equipment. Conversely, other companies, such as Microsoft, have a minor investment in these types of assets. In this chapter, we discuss the proper accounting for the acquisition, use, and disposition of property, plant, and equipment. The text to the right reads, This chapter also includes numerous conceptual and global discussions that are integral to the topics presented here. I F R S Insights related to P P E are presented in Chapter 11.
A chart at the bottom contains five columns containing topics pertaining to the Acquisition and Disposition of Property, Plant, and Equipment. The first column has the title, Property, Plant, and Equipment, and includes acquisition of property, plant, and equipment; cost of land; cost of buildings; cost of equipment; and self-constructed assets. The next column is titled Interest costs during construction, and includes qualifying assets, capitalization period, amount to capitalize, an example, special issues, and observations. The next column is the valuation of property, plant, and equipment, and includes cash discounts; deferred-payment contracts; lump-sum purchases; issuance of stock; exchanges of nonmonetary assets; and other valuation methods. The fourth column is titled costs subsequent to acquisition, and includes additions, improvements and replacements, rearrangement and reinstallation, repairs, and a summary. The last column is the disposition of property, plant, and equipment, and includes the sale of plant assets, involuntary conversions, and miscellaneous problems.
" data-index="60" data-size="%7B%22width%22%3A659%2C%22height%22%3A800%7D">
</figure>
</section>
<div class="bottom hr" data-index="61"><hr data-index="62"></div>
</aside>
<h3 id="h3_0002" data-index="63"><span epub:type="pagebreak" role="doc-pagebreak" title="10-2" id="Page_10-2" data-index="64"></span><span class="red" data-index="65">Watch Your Spending</span></h3>
<p data-index="66">Investments in long-lived assets, such as property, plant, and equipment, are important ­elements in many companies’ balance sheets. Along with research and development, these investments are the driving force in generating cash flows. To provide some insight into the magnitude of these expenditures, the following graph shows how capital expenditures on structures and equipment (whether new or used) have shown steady growth after the effects of the 2008 financial crisis.</p>
<figure data-index="67">
<img class="center" src="https://ereader-books-prod.chegg.com/682/9781119503682/39c53495-be04-40a4-af01-80a39a7df223/OPS/images/c10/w0232.jpg" alt="A stacked bar chart shows expenditures on structures and equipment during period 2002 to 2015. The horizontal axis represents the year, ranging from 2002 to 2015 with an increment of 1 year. The vertical axis represents the current dollars in billions ranging from 0 to $1,800 billion with an increment of $300 billion. A legend indicates that the red portion of each bar is for equipment and the yellow portion is for structures. The data presented in the graph indicate that about $639 billion was spent on equipment and about $359 billion was spent on structures in 2002. After a little drop in 2003, there was a gradual increase in the amount spent on both equipment and structures up through 2008 to about $562 billion on structures and $812 billion on equipment. A significant drop occurred in 2009 to about $450 billion on structures and $641 billion on equipment. During 2010 to 2015, there has been a gradual increase to the peak in 2015 of about $646 billion spent on structures and about $993 billion spent on equipment. 
" data-index="68" data-size="%7B%22width%22%3A1016%2C%22height%22%3A470%7D">
</figure>
<p data-index="69">On an even more positive note, spending on capital projects (including research and development) is on the uptrend in just about all industries, as shown in the following table.</p>
<figure data-index="70">
<div style=" background-color: #FFFDE9; padding: 1em; border: 1px solid #000;" data-index="71">
<table class="bordernone" style=" width: 60%;" data-index="72">
<tbody data-index="73">
<tr data-index="74">
<td data-index="75"></td>
<td colspan="2" data-index="76"><span class="center" data-index="77"><span class="bdr1" data-index="78">Capital Expense (in billions)</span></span></td>
<td data-index="79"></td>
</tr>
<tr data-index="80">
<td style=" width: 30%;" data-index="81"><span class="bdr1" data-index="82">Industry&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></td>
